^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|West Coast players refer to this as the "Walsh Diamond," named after Dick Walsh, West Coast expert of the 60's, who was one of the first successful practitioners of the style. Of course, Kaplan-Sheinwold adherents use this treatment in responding to 1C, although in conjunction with weak notrumps.|
PG| ***** 233 ***** |


AT|

When does a "Walsh" player respond 1D to 1C? As our examples show, about the only hand types are 
^c@2(a) a hand with no major, usually with four or more diamonds, and 
^C@2(b) a full opening bid or better usually with five + diamonds as well as one or two four-card majors. The inferences that opener can draw from this can be very helpful.|
PG| ***** 234 ***** |


AT|

Opener rebidding style of each group will be governed by their respective styles. |
PG| ***** 235 ***** |


AT|

After 1C -1D, Standard bidders must continue the up-the-line search for a major-suit fit. Responder could easily have a major as well as diamonds, so if opener doesn’t show the major, a fit may be lost and responder may have a hand that is too weak for a second bid.|
PG| ***** 236 ***** |


AT|

Walsh players are involved in a very different situation. A 1D responder has denied holding a four-card major unless preparing to reverse on a strong hand. Therefore, opener does not have to show a major if one is held. With a balanced hand, opener should take advantage of the methods used to show the minimum balanced hand by rebidding 1 NT. These players can't miss a major-suit fit since responder will now reverse into a major if one is held.|
pg| ***** 237 ***** |


cp|1|AT|

^*BMM: ^*N|cp||at|A point contested by Pattaya bridge club.|
